name: Costco Wholesale Docklands
review_text:
I've been a long-time member of Costco, and it used to be a go-to place for my business needs. However, recent developments have left me with mixed feelings about this retail giant.

One of the primary reasons for my hesitation is the noticeable price hikes on their membership fees. It's disheartening to see the cost of being a member steadily increase, making it harder for businesses like mine to justify the expense. On top of that, the introduction of more stringent rules and regulations regarding memberships has made the entire shopping experience less convenient and more restrictive.

What initially drew me to Costco was its reputation for offering quality products at competitive prices. Unfortunately, that reputation seems to have faded in recent years. I've found that I can often locate better deals elsewhere, eroding the value proposition that once made Costco so appealing.

Furthermore, the idea of buying in bulk, which is a hallmark of the Costco experience, has its downsides. It often leads to impulse purchases of unnecessary items, which can be detrimental to a business's bottom line. The allure of saving money in the long run can quickly turn into wasted resources.

On a more concerning note, my attempt to address a product quality issue with Costco left me disappointed. I sent them a complaint letter regarding mold on cherries I purchased from them, but I received no meaningful response. This lack of attentiveness to customer concerns speaks volumes about the company's commitment to quality and customer satisfaction.

name: Costco Wholesale Docklands
review_text:
ORDERED:
üçï‚Ää Slice Supreme Pizza ($2.99)
üç© Twisted Churros ($2.99)

REVIEW:
This review will only focus on the food.
The supreme pizza is doughy, with the toppings of olives, capsicum, mushroom and meat placed on top of the melted cheese. This creates a really muddled flavour because nothing is cohesive. Coming in a really generous serving, it's a handful to eat.

Churros were also extremely generous. The seasoning is great, but the dough tastes off. Chewy, and without the crunchy outer edge and fluffy insides. It's probably edible if you bring it home to toast it again... but eating in the food court at Costco is not a great experience even though it's awesome portions for the price.

You can step outside Costco and enter District Docklands, which has a plethora of edible food. Which is worth the money.

name: Costco Wholesale Docklands
review_text: They sell just about everything here....just check out the photos and you'll see what I mean. They sell groceries, deli goods, breads, cakes and confectionery, dairy, meats, poultry, seafood, frozen foods, fruit and vegetables, alcohol, toiletries and cosmetics, supplements, housewares, gift ware, school and office supplies, electrical and electronics goods including computers and TVs, clothing, automotive goods, eye-wear, cleaning and garden supplies and the list goes on. You can also buy window furnishings, tires and even coffins. They also run regular member savings coupons which offer additional discounts on special products. Goods are usually sold in bulk packages so you have to be able to store the extra quantities at home. Prices are usually good but you do have to check as sometimes you can do better at other stores like Aldi. Costco is a membership based warehouse so you have to pay an annual membership fee. A normal consumer which I think they call a Gold Star Member pays $60 per year and businesses like cafes and restaurants pay $55 per year. Parking at this Costco outlet can be difficult especially on weekends.

name: Costco Wholesale Docklands
review_text:
Visited Costco for the first time at the Docklands location. Be warned, they have their own, free for 2 hours, undercover parking. But ONLY for COSTCO members. You need a COSTCO card to enter via the boom gates. We weren't yet members so had to park at the nearby Woolworths carpark, also free for only 90 minutes, then paid. Docklands is a very busy, cluttered area and navigating around can be tricky.
You cannot enter COSTCO, even to look around, unless you are a paid up member, $55-$60year, or a guest of a member.
I must say I found the "joining" experience extremely unpleasant.
Staff were very busy both with new registrations, customer queries, and shop returns. The need to supply Passports, drivers licences or other ID, ABNs (for business membership), have an Identity photo taken etc. quite intrusive, abrupt and unexpected.
There are no explanations we could find at the registration area to let us know what the process required, and no explanatory brochures either.
This is not the place to come for a few odd items.
You come here to buy large quantities of things. A large number of items are recognisable brands, in bulk quantities, and a lot of COSTCOs own brands.
You can buy jewellery, diamond rings etc, with some items over $5000.00, gold bullion, a 500gm ingot for around $43,000.00, Coffins, Car tyres, Garden Sheds, clothes, shoes, fresh groceries, baked goods, meat, dairy, wine and spirits, cleaning products, whitegoods, appliances, Apple phones, computers, cleaning products, automotive items etc etc etc.
Almost anything you can think of.
Plus 2 of the Melbourne COSTCOs sell discounted fuel, in Moorabbin and Epping only.
Not everything is cheaper though! Some branded items are very slightly cheaper, so considering the inconvenience of paying and having to carry and find storage for large quantities negates any saving.
However SOME items are a lot cheaper, real savings are available if you know how much things cost "outside".
We bought a few of their heat and eat, prepared meals, Chicken Tom Yum soup, Quesadillas, Chilli Con Carne, Pork Knuckles, etc. So far each has been really delicious, home cooked/restaurant quality, and I think good value.
This is a huge barn of a place, and just walking around  the entire store, with the giant sized trolleys, can be exhausting if you don't know where everything is.
Definitely the place you can go to for a big shop up, or if you have a large family, business etc.

Recently renewed my membership and only got 10 months valid membership out of 12 months because this policy. Even you haven‚Äôt been to Costco for 2 months they can still charge you. It‚Äôs unfair and take advantage of customers.

Memberships updated within two months after expiration will result in your membership being valid from that expiration date of that year until that same date the following year.

name: Costco Wholesale Docklands
review_text:
Tyres were not installed like what an expert/great tyre center would do.

I bought 5 new tyres with installations. Only to discovered later that:

1) One of the wheels ‚Äúold‚Äù balancing weights have not been removed, but they‚Äôve just added new weights to counter them.

2) The yellow dots on 4 tyres were not aligned to their wheel valves.

The above lapses, or laziness, don‚Äôt instill trust and confidence with regards to expertise and consistent quality of the job. These things, above, matters to me, and it should for other customers if they know enough about tyres.

So I went back a week later to have one wheel/tyre re-done correctly (re-align of yellow dot and,  rebalance and removal of old weights). And I also have to accept the rest of the 4 tyres not having their yellow dots aligned correctly (since it may cause more trouble if I allow touch them).

At minimum, I would expect quality and consistency from an expert work, having:

1) All old weights to be removed carefully and cleanly before re-balancing.

2) The yellow dots on tyres to be alligned with the wheel valves.

3) Wipe off excess compounds, on tyres and wheels, used during fitting.

The above matters, and would instill confidence on quality and expertise, without being reminded or being told to do so.

On my second car, I insisted and therefore got an optimal installation with points #1 & #2 from above.

On the side note, the only other reason not to align the tyre yellow/red dots with the wheel valves is when doing wheel balancing like what racing tyres are done. Otherwise, better off just align the dots with the valves. Oh, the 3rd reason is laziness‚Äîbecause it doesn‚Äôt take time at all doing correctly.

name: Costco Wholesale Docklands
review_text:
Not sure exactly who these people prior to speaking about, but I've always found the customer service lovely at Costco, especially in these situations:

A) I had my wallet stolen, so I didn't have any physical ID and all my cards had also been taken too (thank goodness for cardless cash!), they let me renew the membership and I just needed to provide them with a picture of my drivers licence (it took some digging in my email, but I did find it!) and set up a new card on the spot.

B) Today (29/11/2020) when I went in with my own trolley, the staff member at the door politely let me know that I couldn't use it and even got me a Costco trolley without needing a gold coin (yes, I was frustrated, but the staff members are just following policy and trying their best). When I gave my trolley at the membership desk the gentlemen explained that they had some people stealing large amounts of alcohol via a personal trolley recently (stuffing it at the bottom then covering up with dark material) you can understand that, they wouldn't change the policy like that over $10 cake etc, it would have been major and reoccurring for this to of been implemented.

C) They were so lovely when I asked about a product, they said that it was just by the door (not rudely or anything of the sort).

I will admit though, trying to phone them up can be incredibly frustrating and not getting through etc, that is my only negative.

Yes, the trolleys are huge and yes it can get crowded, but you aren't going into Costco for 5 minutes, you expect to be in there for 30 minutes plus (hot tip - don't go there if you have time constraints and try to get there at the opening time!) So take your time, be courtious, politely let people know if they can step back a little if in 1.5metres and just relax! =)

review_text:
I've been a member for a fair few years. The checkout staff are nice and there are some good products. However the store isn't consistent with the foods they stock. I've even emailed them in the past to confirm if it was just out of stock or permanently removed and unfortunately it's usually the latter.

What really got to me on today's grocery run was after leaving the store, placing the items in my car and heading back to use the toilet. I used the entrance where members sign up as it's the shortest path (with my card). A lady at the 'customer service' desk rudely told me I had to go around. What for? There's no signage saying you need to go around. If it's because of social distancing I'm going to be closer to people by trying to walk through the narrow checkouts than if I went through the first entrance. There's just no logic there. I'm going to the Epping store for the remainder of the membership and probably won't renew it.

She then proceeded to run away with the card and pass it onto ATHENA who ran away with the card and made it look like I had committed a crime. I was so worked up, so I took the card away from ATHENA and went over to have a chat to the "manager" MISTY. He explained to me in a very arrogant tone I couldn't use this membership card and was denied entry. I was so red faced at the fact I was humiliated in front of such a large crowd. The membership card was taken away from me and they said I wasn't allowed to take it and to get out.

I will never visit this store ever again and won't recommend anyone to visit. Not to mention they are much more expensive than the other supermarkets.

MISTY and GENET shouldn't be in customer service at all.

name: Costco Wholesale Docklands
review_text: The advantage of buying tyres at Costco is Lifetime services include inflation pressure checks, tyre balancing, tyre rotations and flat tyre repairs. 2 years ago, I bought a good set of 4 Michelin tyres from Costco at Docklands. 2 days ago, I had a punctured tyre. I brought my car back to repair the punctured tyre. I was served by a tyre centre manager. The Manager inspected the nail on the tyre then quickly claimed that it's not repairable thus not covered by Costco lifetime service policy as the position of the nail is not right in the middle of the tyre. He bombarded me with technical jargons why the repair can't be done and it's dangerous that really confused me. He advised me to change the whole set of 4 tyres. I said my tyres are a very good set of imported tyres and it costs me nearly $1500 only 2 years ago and still look ok. He said not how long I have driven them that matters but what the mileage that I've done is matter. I asked him to check on Costco computer system. He then admitted that I have only done 40,000km which is very average for 2 years. He then advised me to change 1 tyre for $352. I said I need to get a second opinion. He said to me that whoever is going to fix the tyre must be a professional. I said I don't buy no brand tyres and I don't use no name business. I drove back to Richmond and popped in at Tyreplus Richmond. The Manager (I don't know him) came out look at the nail and gave me a smile then drove my car into the workshop without asking me any questions to make me feel uncomfortable. 10 minutes later he came back to the office where I was waiting and charged me only $50. I've started to question about the integrity of Costco tyre services.

name: Costco Wholesale Docklands
review_text:
Went there for the first time, wanted to ask the old lady at the entry where to register a membership card and she told me : Don't block the trolley behind.

So, I noticed the registration counter, I went there to queue up, told the front desk guy I would like to apply for membership card, he just ask me to fill up the form and then he just disappear(which I actually got a few questions filling up the form).

After finish filling up the form except the ID section. Then, there is this weird Asian guy (he will give you a fake smile but also can be really rude, like looking down on people that you can't afford a membership or are  you even 18), I asked him that which types of ID I have to filled in and he was like NO WE DON'T NEED YOUR ID and just took my pen to cross that out and give the form back to me and walk away. I was puzzled for awhile and called him more than 5 times after he chit-chat with other staff. He only came back to me and asked me for proof that I stayed in the address provided. So, I showed him but I can feel that he felt a bit annoyed (On my mind : Hello, you get paid to work here and a lot of people out there is unemployed you should be grateful or do what you should do before you got sack?)

review_text:
The staff at Costco Docklands have always been friendly, so this is definitely an exception, alas there are always black sheep amongst. Unfortunately, such staff do leave a bad impression on an otherwise friendly and welcoming environment. I was at the Cashier and did witness a cashier called Samia B treating a customer ahead of me rudely and inappropriately.

The customer ahead of me was paying his bill $12x.25 approx in cash , and took out some notes, I believe,  $150 and placed it on the cashier table while getting his coins out so that he can get exact change. The cashier took the notes and started counting out the change for $150 payment. When the customer wanted to give her coins, so that he would have only notes as change, she just went ' it's too late' ,without even looking at the customer and with her cash till still open. When the customer said that he was just going to give her the coins, she ignored him completely without any comments and just put his change, receipt and membership card in his open hands, with no eye contact with him at all, and started processing my order. Just to be clear there was not a long queue.

The customer was  shock for a moment before being upset and did say some unpleasant things about her attitude. She just said "please do not swear at me", again with no eye contact  and called for the supervisor.

Later, I did tell the supervisor that I who witness the whole scenario am disgusted with how Samia treated the customer, and still called the supervisor as though how she treated her customer was nothing wrong,  and do hope that they do follow up this case.

review_text:
12:30pm 6/4/2019, crowded Saturday afternoon with very long queues at all of the checkout counters as usual. As I was walking to the nearest counter, I saw a male staff just removed the "This counter is closed" red sign on that counter and a female staff was moving the blocking chained trolleys out of the cart way next to it. Thought they were getting ready to start checking out on that counter, I waited for a while and when that female staff with the name JENNY S. went back behind the counter, I nicely asked her if she was going to opened that counter as a friendly customer. But for my most surprisingly shopping experiences, she said: "What if i don't open this counter now?" with a smirk appeared on her face. I could not believe my ears then asked her again. She repeated: "What if i don't open this counter now? You will have to get in lines" I was so shocked with what she said but still kept calm and proceeded to take my membership card out for her. When finished, JENNY S just held my card and receipt out, did not even look at my face let alone say thank you and a goodbye.
What was wrong with her? I was at that counter first, nobody else before me, so what line she wanted me to get in??? Other counters lines? Then why did she open that counter???
Costco Docklands, I did not pay for my membership to be treated with the awful attitude and ignorant liked that. JENNY S  is THE RUDEST retail worker I have ever met. Never come back to Costco Docklands again!

review_text: Wanted to speak about the food court there.Not only the price the food is really tasty .Cheeseburger for $7 and all famous $1.99 hotdogs with pepsi.I loved the food court wilth all american feel.Went there to view outdoor furnitures and American brands .Hard Drinks they sale are not cheap but they have variety.I believe the pastry and cake are the best  in my opinion.They do have some fantastic furniture option everyone must check if they are buying cheap comfortable furniture .All in all a good place to do shopping .

name: Costco Wholesale Docklands
review_text:
There‚Äôs a huge selection of everything at Costco, ranging from homewares, electrical items, clothing, food, groceries.
The displays are very well thought out and you will be satisfied at every aisle. Do make a comparison with Aldi, Coles and Woolworths before you go crazy buying everything.
I find the price for stuff like Contigo bottles, thermos bottles and sausages are very good. Electronics like Tv are pretty good too, if you compare to Harvey Norman or Good Guys. The books selection is wonderful too and children will be spoilt for hours with the books.
Parking at this Costco can be quite stressful as there are a lot of shoppers at this Costco, and waiting for the lift with your trolley can be quite a nightmare. So with regards to the parking issue, I would very much prefer the Costco located at Epping as the parking at Epping is an open air car park and you would not need to wait for the lift to bring you to the underground parking.

name: Costco Wholesale Docklands
review_text: BEWARE new members! scam alert! i came and tried to sign up for business membership, Michelle from registration desk had absolutely no idea what a business is and asked me why my business is registered under a company and trust?? and wanted to reject my business registration!! then went on to tell me she would accept it as an exception for me but due to this exception i would not be allowed to add a 2nd person in..then because she was so annoyed, she mispelt the business name on my card...i went back in 2 weeks later to get the card changed to the correct name ...and got this fixed but was told the 2nd person i nominated on my card named John would also need to come in to fix his card.. I informed the assistant that i did not add a second person but was told there is a second person added, i can only assume it would be Michelle's friend or relative...absolutely fraud... so she tells me i cannot add a second person so that she can add her family member?? criminal! the manager David called me back but the only incredible explanation he gave me was we had to pair you up with a random person to get a free cooler bag as part of the deal..what cooler bag?? what deal??, i was never told about this and was certainly never given one...and even if you pair me up with a second person as part of some unknown deal, why is that person registered as second member under my card membership....dodgy, beware!!

review_text:
Went to Costco about one month ago for the first time. It was absolutly breathtaking. I was warmly welcomed and as I entered all my fears and problems disappeared constantly. My heartbeat went faster as I wandered through the golden shining corridors. My mind was blown when I discovered the food court. The food is extremly healthy and I lost about 30 pounds since my first visit. Never have I experienced a more passionate customer service than at Costco. I am friends with almost all of the staff and when I feel down I just pay Costco a visit and they cheer me up.
So what I am trying to say is this: Do not listen to all the salty people and haters, who are just not able to appreciate the glory of Costco with all their heart. They are probably mostly Coles employees and don't know how to cope with the fact that they picked the wrong employer.

Have a great day and Hail Costco!

name: Costco Wholesale Docklands
review_text: I was a member at Costco for the last three years.  However, over the last 12 months when auto-renewal was pushed, Costco prices have been increasing to the extent it is no longer competitive for a members only business model.  Soft drinks are cheaper at Aldi, desserts are cheaper at Aldi; Dan Murphy has reduced liquor prices to compete with Costco; Target and Myer clothing prices compete with Costco; JB Hifi computer is cheaper than Costco.  It used to be that I could pay $60 and not worry about shopping for prices.  I can't do that anymore and will not be renewing my membership.  Customer service is good.  The same as what I get at other retailers.

The dairy section is cheap (cheapest eggs in Melbourne), some of the clothing on special is good value, but not everything is the cheapest in town.

The best way to describe prices is that they are similar to Coles when they are on special but not as cheap as there weekly sales but when Coles doesn‚Äôt have it on sale Costco everyday prices are always cheaper.

The churros was basically thick dense dough with cinnamon sugar. It was cold, dry and hard, you could easy use it as a weapon.  Save your money, you're better off putting cinnamon sugar on cardboard.

review_text: I came to Costco on Thursday  the 7th of June in the evening about 7:30pm and wanted to have a bite to eat before shopping as I always spend at least $500 here and shopping hungry increases my spend. I was humiliated as I walked in with my family member because we entered on the food side/ exit. As the man at the door chased us down like fellons the 4 employees behind the sign up counter all shouted and reprimanded us for entering through the exit despite the fact that I showed my card. I'm so embarassed I will never return. Despite turning around and being escorted out so we could walk around the entrance when we finally left with our purchases the same individual at the exit gave us disapproving looks and didn't say a word or even greet us as he signed off our receipt. I felt like absolute rubbish.

name: Costco Wholesale Docklands
review_text:
A great membership warehouse where prices for bulk items can provide savings. Some prices are not all that cheap so it pays to check prices elsewhere before making a bulk purchase. Membership is via a yearly payment to obtain a membership card which must be provided on every entry to and from the car park, when entering the front door and purchasing at the checkout.

You can purchase lots of different items here from washing machines to alcohol, plenty of frozen and packaged goods meats, fruit and vegetables and the Warehouse has plenty of consumer items to choose from.

There is a takeaway with reasonable prices and also a car tyre repair shop. There is an Undercover car parking for members only.

Access when arriving by car is quite quick via CityLink onto Footscray Road or public transport by tram into Docklands.

Literally screeching at myself and partner to get out of the line. Soon found out this was a fake event promoting membership discounts for defence and ex defence members like myself. There was no discount. Marketing received said first 100 through door got a free bag, it was not clear that this was only for members and we were told we had to sign up to get the bag. No one scanned our Defence tickets so it was clearly anotger sign of a fake event. CostCo management should be ashamed of themselves making out they are doing something to help Defence community while all it was trying to suck in more people to pay $60 membership.  Its not even that cheap. Save yourself the drive and go to Aldi.

name: Costco Wholesale Docklands
review_text:
My wife is American and looks forward to hosting thanksgiving each year for our family and friends and we do most of our shopping for that day at Costco.

As we will be unable to make it to Melbourne on the couple of remaining weekends leading up to thanksgiving we decided to make a flying visit to Costco today - Melbourne Cup day. I had the day off and although my wife had to work she was able to leave at 4pm.

We had checked the website which confirmed the store was open until 8:30pm.

Even today the website says the store is open until 8:30pm.

We arrived at the store at about 5:50pm and to our horror was told we were the last to be allowed in and  we had 5 to 10 mins to do our shopping and the the store would close at 6pm!!!! I asked the attendant at the door why the store was closing and she replied "it's a public holiday".

I pointed out that their web site did not mention the store would be closing early nor did the list of public holidays they are closed displayed near the entrance include Melbourne Cup Day.

She referred me to the manager but I was not in the mood to discuss calmly the disappointment, anger, the wasted time and expense in travelling from Bendigo to Melbourne (approx 11/2 hours), shop for less than 10 mins then turn around and drive home again!

You need to realise you have country customers too Costo so show some decency and keep them informed by making sure the info. On your website is current to the day.

I remain yours,
Sincerely Pissed Off.

I bought my hearing aid in Costco Docklands initially. Due to my work I was using Epping store last 10 years. They convinced me technology has changed to buy modern hearing aid 3 and half years ago. They send it away after the payment, because warranty period is finished. I was mentioned 10 business days it takes. As I followed it has arrived, but they can not be bothered to let me know. To adjust to my hearing they do not have time till 2 more weeks. I am surprised at their way of talking. When I went few times for shopping hardly no one was in hearing aid centre. Suddenly they were fully booked for 2 weeks. If I want I can collect the hearing aid from the front desk that was the exact words by the lady. They are trying to get rid of the customers, only interested to make them to buy a unit. After we bought no service. If this is the case I will take my business somewhere-else. No need to come to Costco. Initial Audiologist from docklands store is good. We only bought from there due to their service. Otherwise I would not prefer Costco to buy hearing aid at all.

name: Costco Wholesale Epping
review_text:
Costco Epping is a one stop shop for families who want to buy in bulk and also fill up with fuel. They have one of the lowest fuel rates in Melbourne but the queue could be very long.
The parking for the store is well laid out and plenty of spots are available all the time.
The products are typical to all Costco so there are no surprises here.
The food options here are limited with the majority of menu items catering to the non-vegetarian.
Very limited veg options and it is a shame.
The tyre section is great too where the staff is helpful and knowledgeable.
Their bubble tea is not great and it is like bubble tea slurpy and is not pleasant to drink if you have great boba tea/pearl tea standards.
They also sell one of the best Madelaines I have ever had so check that out too.
Pro Tip: if you want to buy toilet tissues or kitchen towels then go in the morning as the stock usually gets over pretty quick.
PS: They also sell coffins here!!!!

Mums this place shouldn't be a kindergarten for your 7 children to be running through aisles... keep them at home. The price of food here is expensive but you get what you get....

This place also felt very dirty, trash in the carpark. Trash in the aisles...

All up that's my review.

name: Costco Wholesale Epping
review_text:
Though it's a great place to shop, they're quite inconsistent with their stock. For example, last week there were Walnuts available and when I went this week there were none there. I don't know what supplier agreements they have but they keep on changing their suppliers e.g., they used to stock Red Tractor organic oats but it's no where to be seen now and replaced by some other company.
In a nutshell, you might not find the same item that you're after on your next visit (which is pretty annoying for such a large player to be doing this and also charging an annual fee). To top it up, they also don't mention any ETA when the stock will be available or just put a sign mentioning the reason why it's not available and if there are any chances in future it ever will be stocked?
N.B - it's also a junk food haven!

name: Costco Wholesale Epping
review_text:
Yesterday 16 November approximately 1245 I was driving to Epping Costco petrol to full my car (1.16 for premium) after filling my car I noticed that my car would not start.

I had a flat battery, I immediately informed the petrol attendant whom was very helpful in putting witches hats around our car for safe zoning and informed me that Costcos sell car batteries.

I then went to Costcos shop to purchase a brand new car battery $133 which is a bargain.

On arrival to my car the petrol attendant was very helpful as he himself assisted in changing out battery.

I‚Äôd like to thanks the petrol attendant on showing there are great people out there whom show a can do attitude, knowledge and pride in their company. People like this is why I shop at Costcos and will continue to. I have told most of my friends what he has done for me and will recommend Costcos for all shoppers.

review_text:
I cancelled my membership primarily because of rude disinterested staff.

Secondly I returned the horrible dry black Forrest cake and a puma hoodie on the same day I cancelled my membership.

I bought the hoodie two days earlier and it was the wrong size so when I went in to purchase the cake I bought another hoodie at the correct size at this point not knowing I was going to cancel my membership of some 10 years.

I‚Äôve always been visually impressed by the cakes but never purchased one. It was a flop.

The staff member could refund without me being a member as it was faulty!

The hoodie was classed as ‚Äúchange of mind‚Äù even though they could see I purchased one two days earlier as well as one when I purchased the cake that day.

After asking for the manager I was able to get a refund. Why do I always have to ask for the manager to get service?  If it is out of scope for the team member to process it surely they can call the manager rather than lecturing me on their ‚Äúpolicy‚Äù

Next thing was the person that was serving me was the same person who provided poor customer service earlier. She actually asked me why I canceled my membership and I said ‚Äúdidn‚Äôt your manager speak to you about it?‚Äù It was now 4 hours later.

No the manager hadn‚Äôt!!

The next morning I called customer service and explained why I cancelled my membership to be told it wasn‚Äôt good enough.

Now a week later it still isn‚Äôt good enough. They assured me they would investigate and call me back.

No call. Guess they are busy not improving customer service!

review_text: I have been to this place few times. Staffs are friendly. I like the fact there is a fuel station in case you running low on fuel. I like purchasing in bulk from Costco I get affordable deals sometimes and a tasty variety of different foods and items at affordable price.

name: Costco Wholesale Epping
review_text:
Great for grocery shopping, Kirkland brands are especially great value. Sometimes Australian brand prices are still the same with local shops even though you're buying bulk.

Fuel station is also often the cheapest price in the area, although sometimes it can get very busy. It should be more clear that the pumps can reach either side of vehicles.

The food court offers some great fast food, although the layout of the seating and the lack of management for the shopping trolleys is very disappointing. Shoppers are squashed in tight seating while the massive shopping trolleys block the already tight walkways between the tables.

Trolleys should be parked in a distinct area with a ticket system where customers can leave them while they eat

My wife and I arrived at the warehouse a couple of minutes past 18:00 to find the doors closed. Not one bit of info on the ordering page or the acknowledgment email that followed, indicated that the warehouse had adjusted hours for Christmas eve and would close at 17:00 instead of 20:30 as usual for a Tuesday.

It defeated the purpose of becoming a member and we will not be renewing it when it expires.

name: Costco Wholesale
review_text:
My review is all about the people who work here and some recommendations for improvements. They are terrific! Always helpful and friendly. They are empathetic too, which is really rare to find these days.
In regards to the store itself, I recommend management make the following improvements:
- put swivel wheels on the rear of the trolleys! They are very difficult to manoeuvre especially when the store is busy with customers. I can imagine it would be difficult for people with disabilities.
- recommend certain products be stacked in a way that make it easier to lift into your trolley. E.g. boxes of coke are stacked high and in a herringbone criss cross manner, which makes it a WHS hazard. One day a box is going to fall and hit a customer when they try to grab a box of coke.
- the area outside the dairy cool room is cluttered with merchandise, which causes a bottleneck when customers try to navigate through this area.

name: Costco Wholesale
review_text:
What can you write about an international supermarket? That it is humongous, sells everything in bulk, staff are mostly indifferent (some quite helpful though), prices are cheap etc.
Oh wait! Prices are not always cheaper. Last few times I have compared prices with Woolies, Coles and Costco, and found that some items are comparable or cheaper at our local supermarkets. In one instance I found that the bulk purchase was costlier than the individual item. :/

Still, we do find the overall experience isn't bad. So far, I have found that the staff are in general friendly. My biggest frustration is that they don't have a system which helps customers find items easily. You also can't find staff to help you.

The canteen is now open again and you can go to eating cheesy and delicious pizzas, fries, hot dogs with refillable sodas. :)

That's Costco.

review_text:
This beautiful one star is awarded to the checkout operator - Anita M for her discriminative behaviour against Asian customers, on her shift at register 01, around 11:00am at Ringwood Costco.

(1) She deliberately pushed a box of strawberry and 2 boxes of eggs off the conveyor belt of register. Not a minimal sign of apology.

(2) Cold and rude face from the first scan till the tendering. In the end, she warned me about not trying to pay using credit cards which do not belong to member (me). I showed her the name of payment card is exactly my name and she simply ignored, turned away and repeated the same words once more.

(3) No greetings. No goodbye. No eye contacts.

Another kind staff has quickly cleaned up the mess and picked up the replacement for us.

Returned to the store and asked for refund for the box of strawberry as most of content in it are rotten ones (we left in a rush so did not check, not blaming on this). and cancelled the membership (been happily with Costco for 13 years since Dockland's launch in 2009) in the afternoon.

I hope I did not exaggerate any details. I cannot figure out any other reasons why my parents and I were treated like this, other than an act of xenophobia. Suggestion to the store manager and customer service team are a review / investigation the surveillance footage and behaviours of the aforementioned staff.

name: Costco Wholesale
review_text:
We love Costco! They have pretty much everything you could possibly need, want & more!

Great for groceries, day to day items for the house, garden, clothing, shoes, gifts, etc. As well as other services with membership such as tyres, optical, etc. (Bonus if you are near petrol locations too..)

Love the huge variety of meat. The fruit, vegetables & bakery items are lways fresh & highest quality. Last a lot longer than other places.

It has especially been great during Covid-19. Helped at times when other shops had no stock. Certainly helps with having items BULK or even just larger individual products compared to the other supermarkets. Took away the stress of running around between other shops trying to get what we needed.

The ONLY down fall is the lack of variety for PETS. Food selection can be limited especially if you have a fussy fur baby!

The membership cost pays for itself by the time you add up savings over 1-2 shops depending on how much you buy/need.

name: Costco Wholesale
review_text: Great bulk purchasing prices. Very reasonable priced roasted pistachios and macadamia nuts. Quick bites at exit eg large pizza slice for under $3. name: Costco Wholesale
review_text:
I have been a member since 2012. Costco Australia was pretty good those days... Similar to Costco Canada and US..
COSTCO is starting to become a doggy supermarket..... where is your quality going? Apples are fully waxed... The 3 litre milk expires in 5 days!! The lettuce 4 pack, you can find live flies and mosquitoes in there.....
Today Costco Australia is just like Myer and David Jones..... Overpriced, even more expensive than the manufacturers of the products and even more expensive than The Good Guys. example attached: Gopro hero 9 bundle pack $589 by manufacturer... $699 at Costco.... and if you ask them why, they just say our Costco Online division is different.... "No it's not. You both operate in the same country under the same name." For me "the customer", I want the product with a good price." You do not even price match your online store.(Example 2: Arlo Ultra V2 advertised Costco online $1,249. Price in Costco store $1,449. Tried to order online and it was not available. They said no longer in stock. Went to their store they had plenty but didn't price match their online business.  Price at Good Guys is $1200 with 3 cameras plus an additional camera.
Why should I pay for membership when you are no longer Costco and you are operating like Myer, Coles and Woolworths and your prices are going up and up ... the only cheaper thing you offer now is Fuel, which is too far from Ringwood. I spend yearly about 25k at Costco and I am not happy for the service that I am getting today.

name: Costco Wholesale
review_text:
Today, I went to purchase the cooked pork ribs which all of my family love so much, and I found 3 hairs in total in one single rib! That's ridiculous, and none of my family have that colour and length so it's definitely from the shop.

I have always been a regular customer of Costco Ringwood, and I never thought a well-developed chain store will have hygiene problems especially during the current COVID 19 pandemic.

If it is only one hair, I would think that may be a mistake and it's forgivable. When I discovered the second one, it makes me feel uncomfortable, and start questioning the food safety rules that are implemented in Costco.  When I found out the third one, I got really angry and upset, it is unacceptable and unforgivable to make such big negligence on hygiene. I feel disgusting!!!  I would definitely rate absolutely no star if I can!!!

I will not visit Costco Ringwood ever again and I hope everyone who see this review can be more curious when they have the food from Costco and make sure there is no hair inside!

I've attached the photos of the ribs with the hair, it might be hard to see from the ribs but I really don't want to touch the ribs at all. Imagine I found one in my mouth and then the second one...the third one.....

review_text:
Very bad experience at there. It was my first time been there today. Except some of the bulk package items are slightly cheaper than other, most of the stuffs' price is quiet similar comparing with Coles or Woolies. Beside the little disappointment, the most uncomfortable experience was that, I bought 3 hot dogs at the food court after we check out, my husband went to get the drinks at the food court, and I was standing outside the food court eating area, because we were planning to leave after he got the drinks, so I quick bit on my hot dog, a lady whom wearing the uniform just very rude and loud to say "you can't eat inside shopping centre, you should eat outside', then she quickly moved to the return counter to say something, then back to food court eating area again, warning the food court staff to request clients to check in if they want to enter the eating area. She is short with long curved hair, I didn't see her face as I was in shock. I know she was doing her duty to manage the shop, but the way of her performance is awful. I couldn't believe as a manager (I suppose so), whom didn't understand how to serve client in a proper way, even I was wrong to eat inside the shopping centre, but why don't you say please enter the eating area to eat? Help people to understand your rule in a nice way? She just showed off like a queen in the shopping centre, all the people must obey her, go down on her knees. Costco, if you want to continue to hire this kind of person to look after your business, go ahead. I never come back again.
I have to say, the lady who was looking after the food court eating area is very kind, she is an ideal customer service manager candidate.

name: Costco Wholesale
review_text: Costco is an ideal store as it offers good deals, it's even better if you have a family because most of the items are sold in bulk so you don't have to keep on visiting the shops repeatedly.  There is a variety of goods in Costco like clothes, food, appliances, hearing-aids, glasses and much more. However to shop at Costco you need to be a member. The membership fee is $55 annually , you might think that it's a waste of money but you actually save loads. Costco also facilitates private covered parking for your vehicle, Costco Wholesale Ringwood is located right beside Eastland. One great thing about Costco is that there are lots of tasting stations so you can taste new items, there is also a cafeteria where you can purchase Pizza, French-Fries, Hot-Dog, Ice-Cream, Bubble Tea and lots more. There are lots of positives about Costco however the staff is not that great. Overall Costco is a great store with a wide range of items at a low price. ( This review is not intended to cause any offense as it is an opinion).

name: Costco Wholesale
review_text:
I love Costco!!! This place is not just about buying in bulk but it has lots of really good quality items some of which are not readily available anywhere else.

They have good larger sizes for things like   organic flaxseed, cold pressed coconut oil, almond flour, raw nuts, and all cheaper than going to a wholefoods merchant. Some good items for paleo and keto cooking too.

Apart from food, they stock things like Bodum double walled glasses, air fryers, Kitchenaids, LED lights and bulbs, car accessories, etc.

I would highly recommend touring the place if you're interested in becoming a member. And go on a weekday or evenings before they close as it's less busy.

Me and my family are frequent customers at Costco and have not once encountered any bad shopping experience - not until today. While helping my dad pick out a couple of t-shirts i would always fold and put them back as how i found them. It did took us about 30 - 40 minutes for there weren't many sizes available. However, as i was looking around i over heard two workers whispering to each other along the lines of, "she's only looking around, messing up the place and not purchasing" as well as giving me the stare. This made me felt very sick and uncomfortable for such words were being exchanged. I just hope Costco can take note of this because it's not the type of service i would want anyone to encounter.

name: Costco Wholesale
review_text:
Like nothing else in Australia. Costco is unique here.
Most items are purchased in bulk although the savings are minimally effective as they know the market and just slightly undercut the competition. On the plus side, they offer some or many products you cannot purchase elsewhere in Australia.
Their pricing could be cheaper, for my wife and I (just the two of us) we probably couldn't justify our membership. Buying non perishables in bulk means our otherwise $80-120 shop becomes $60-80 and we spend $300+ two or three times per year.
If you have a family or larger household, it's great. We just love the variety and north American offerings.

name: Costco Wholesale
review_text:
Costco is ,of  course, best value to those who buy in bulk... which really isn't myself..but as a shopper I can see others who do save a lot of money by buying in bulk.
The range of products available is huge... from bulk stationary, confectionary, toiletries, meats, vegetables...and if you overindulge in these things..you can purchase (or rather your family can) a coffin...
Yes I wrote coffin.  ....after all I did tell you the product range is vast.
The mixed berry muffins are amazing..huge!!! One muffin can stretch to two people. 2x packs of six cost $9.99    ...Great for work place morning tea..
Black cherry danishes..even beat the muffins.. 2x packs of six for around $12.00 ..( that is a dozen in total...I  won't say to share between 2 people because they are way to good to share.)

Last but not least... the cooked chook...$7.00 and Huge... but not a scratch on the Danishesüòä

Costco is definitely worth the membership...if only for the danishes

name: Costco Wholesale
review_text: Costco Wholesales stores and Warehouses are a good place to find all your housing needs! Anything from laundry items needed and kitchen cleaning items needed, bathroom goods and items and most foods you may want from canned goods to fresh foods, meat, vegetables, coffees and tea's, sugar and sweeteners and most other goods such as rices, pastas, flours and snack etc, gourmet foods and pretty much most things you can find in a supermarket! They also have most kitchen utensils, pots, pans and most other cooking and kitchen needs! Emergency kits and supplies! Costco is also a great place to shop regularly as the prices are very decent and very fair and if you shop there for most of your household goods and needs including your weekly food and grocery needs you can make substantial savings over the course of a year you can save hundreds of dollars or even more if you require large weekly shopping needs if you have a large family for example! I prefer to do most of my shopping and grocery needs there for several reasons 1: the prices save me quite a lot over time, 2: they usually have everything that I want and need due to the fact they are very large outlets and have a very large variety, especially for my meats and poultry goods because I am a gym junkie so to speak and eat a lot of very high protein foods so bulk meats also save me a lot of money over time aswell! I used to have to go to a couple supermarkets and smaller grocery shops to buy everything I want and need but now I can get 90% + of everything I want and need from one location at discount prices! I recommend to anyone with a large family or just large shopping needs to atleast go to Costco and give them a try! I also know people that run cafe's and restaurants that buy a lot of their bulk food needs like rice, pasta, flour etc also buy from Costco due to practicality and prices and they save a decent amount of money! Costco night not be for everyone but I atleast recommend giving them a try! You can find a Costco wharehouse/store close to all central and outet suburbs and more are opening all the time!

name: Costco Wholesale
review_text:
9th April 2019 at 07:28pm Colin T was serving me at food service counter.. I was requesting him that I need some hot water for my little boy, he told me about the policy of Costco that he is not allowed to give any hot water from the coffee machine or anywhere from food service area & advised to see the person who is standing for customer service with vest or jacket for seeking help.
I stayed with my boy and my wife went to request him for some hot/warm water. To make it hassle free & quicker, my wife bought a pepsi cup from the counter and went to meet the person as advised.
He wanted to provide hot/warm water for my little boy baby & asked the person next to him to get some water from the pantry/staff room but very clever minded ‚ÄúALEX‚Äù who is employed since 2013 replied the hot water machine is not working.
Then my wife was requesting him whether he can give permission to the food centre staff to give her some hot water? Then he started to make the story that the coffee machine does vend water but it comes mixed up with milk, that wouldn‚Äôt be good & the water comes very slowly.
Anyway, that‚Äôs what my wife says it is like anyhow he won‚Äôt give us hot water. And he is showing causes like we are uneducated people.
I understand, Costco may not have the policy to provide any hot water to the customer on request & the staffs are not bound to give hot water to any customers.
Then I was thinking I‚Äôm at least that much civilised that I wouldn‚Äôt be refusing any human if any one ask for a little water for a baby boy. Then I have started to ask again to other staffs to help me. I got someone who understood my situation & gave me water.
Anyone can say that It was my fault that why I didn‚Äôt bring hot water for my boy, right?? But I was in a situation that‚Äôs why I was seeking help from other human not the animals. I wasn‚Äôt expecting animal behaviour from look a like a human called Alex.
At end I went back to Human look a like ALEX & was asking him how do you know the hot water is not working & my second question was when did you use the hot water machine last time?? His answers were not relevant then I just requested him to show some manners to humans & left and collected his name from the batch..
COSTCO is a huge company, they do donations as well, even they are collecting donations at check out from every customers. Where The staffs are not that much kind enough to the customers. Not all of them but some of them even didn‚Äôt learn how to show good manners. But there still have good people that‚Äôs why I got that hot water at end.

I am requesting to the management & the big bosses to educate your employees to do nice behaviour & to show good manners to their customers..

Thanking you...

name: Costco Wholesale Moorabbin
review_text:
Step into the bustling aisles of Costco Morabin, a retail paradise that promises an unforgettable shopping experience. As you enter, the sheer size of the store engulfs you, with towering shelves reaching towards the heavens, laden with an endless array of products.

Your senses are immediately awakened by the symphony of sounds and sights. The aroma of freshly baked goods wafts through the air, tempting you to indulge in a sweet treat. The vibrant colors of fresh produce catch your eye, inviting you to explore a cornucopia of fruits and vegetables that promise both nourishment and flavor.

The hustle and bustle of shoppers fills the space, creating an energetic atmosphere. Shopping carts glide along the polished floors, laden with oversized packages and hidden treasures waiting to be discovered. Everywhere you turn, friendly staff members are ready to assist, their knowledge and enthusiasm guiding you through the retail maze.

Venturing further into the store, you encounter the treasure trove of bulk goods that Costco is renowned for. Towering stacks of merchandise await, offering incredible value for money. From household essentials to electronics, clothing to appliances, the options seem limitless. You find yourself marveling at the sheer variety, feeling a sense of excitement as you uncover hidden gems and score unbeatable deals.

One of the standout features of Costco Morabin is its sampling stations, scattered throughout the store like oases of delight. Here, you can tantalize your taste buds with an array of culinary delights, from savory cheeses and artisanal meats to decadent desserts. Each bite is a glimpse into the world of gastronomic pleasures, a momentary escape from the hustle and bustle of the shopping experience.

As you navigate the store, you can't help but be amazed by the efficiency and organization that permeate every corner. The neatly arranged displays, the strategic placement of products, and the seamless checkout process all contribute to a streamlined shopping journey. It's a testament to the dedication and meticulousness of the Costco team, ensuring that your experience is nothing short of exceptional.

While Costco Morabin offers an extensive range of products and an invigorating shopping environment, I must admit that the sheer size of the store can be overwhelming at times. Navigating the expansive aisles and locating specific items may require a bit of extra effort. However, this minor inconvenience is quickly overshadowed by the excitement of discovering new products and enjoying the incredible savings that Costco offers.

In conclusion, Costco Morabin is a retail haven that promises an adventure for the senses. From the vibrant colors to the enticing aromas, every visit is an opportunity to indulge in a retail experience like no other. Whether you're stocking up on household essentials, hunting for bargains, or simply enjoying the thrill of the hunt, Costco Morabin is a destination that won't disappoint.

name: Costco Wholesale Moorabbin
review_text:
I have visited several Costcos in the past and never had a bad experience. However, at this particular Costco, the treatment was appalling. I was spending some time there, leisurely walking around to check out the special offers when, unexpectedly, security approached my friend and me, accusing us of stealing. They insisted on inspecting our bags, which we reluctantly allowed. Despite finding nothing, they threatened to have us escorted. To make matters worse, they even took unauthorized photos of my friend. The lines are excessively long, and the general lack of significant discounts, aside from a few food items, adds to the disappointment. Towards the end of my visit, I decided to voice my concerns to the security guard. In response, he displayed indifference, stating that he didn't mind losing customers and wouldn't lose any sleep, while also threatening to involve the police‚Äîalthough it was unlikely they would take any action. If they suspected me of theft, they should have checked the price of my glasses and compared it to the value of the items they suspected.

PS: The only redeeming aspect I found, which appeared to be a bargain, was a hotdog in exchange for the $60 membership fee. It was rather ironic if you ask me! üòÇ Ultimately, I decided to cancel my membership. If you want to find the best prices, I recommend shopping online instead of wasting $60 on a membership that they can keep to themselves.

name: Costco Wholesale Moorabbin
review_text: Costco in Australia is a shopper's paradise, offering fantastic bulk buying deals that can save you a lot of money. The variety of items they sell is impressive, with everything from groceries and household goods to electronics and furniture. What's even better is the great quality of each item, ensuring that you get your money's worth. To take advantage of these deals, you do need a membership, but it's worth it for the savings you'll make. Plus, one close relative can get a second free pass, making it even easier to shop. Just remember that you need to be in person to sign up, so make sure to plan accordingly. Overall, Costco in Australia is a great option for anyone looking to save money and buy quality products in bulk.

name: Costco Wholesale Moorabbin
review_text:
This place is great for shopping just about everything. It sells a big range of merchandise including groceries, deli goods, breads, cakes and confectionary, dairy, meats, poultry, seafood, frozen foods, fruit and vegetables, alcohol, toiletries and cosmetics, supplements, houseware, giftware, school and office suppplies, electrical and electronics goods including computers and TVs, clothing, automotive goods, eyewear, cleaning and garden supplies and the list goes on. At the Moorabbin store you can also buy window furnishings, garden sheds, tyres, petrol (at good prices) and even coffins.

Costco also runs regular member savings coupons which offer additional discounts on special products. Goods are usually sold in bulk packages so you have to be able to store the extra quantities at home. Prices are usually good but you do have to check as sometimes you can do better at other stores like Aldi.

Costco is a membership based warehouse so you have to pay an annual membership fee. A normal consumer which I think they call a Gold Star Member pays $60 per year and businesses like cafes and restaurants pay $55 per year.

The good thing about this Costco outlet is that it has plenty of parking and sells cheap petrol.

name: Costco Wholesale Moorabbin
review_text: We‚Äôve been members since 2009 and I‚Äôm staggered to see such diversity in customer reviews. I‚Äôve been a fan since visiting Costco in America. Although some here clearly complain about their experience  in 9 years of shopping here each and every time it‚Äôs been a great experience. Our kids LOVE it when we say it‚Äôs time to go - we make a night of it often filling 2 trolleys. The entire building is clean like no other if it‚Äôs kind. It makes Campbell‚Äôs cash m carry and bulk buy places look like a joke. They stock great product, often only one or two of a kind -  but they are the best in that category. I had a Kitchen-aid Food Processor that although was bought 7 years ago - it has been used twice - the latch broke and I took it back -  They happily gave me a full credit - try getting Myers or David Jones or ANY other retailer to refund you $345 for a faulty product 7 years later. Good luck. Impossible is the answer to that. But Costco protect you the customer. And  that makes you feel safe and confident as a customer buying from them. Sure not everything is cheaper - but often most everything is very comparable or at least cheaper. Not faultless I agree. But who is? I‚Äôm not. Let alone the Costco competition - they are not In The same race. And the membership fee is recouped In just 4 tanks of petrol - particularly if you run on 98 octane. Brilliant.

name: Costco Wholesale Moorabbin
review_text:
This is my regular Costco, well worth the journey up from the regional area I live in.

Was here on the 23rd of April to purchase some Square pay readers and docks, had Matthew help me find them on the floor and let me know that they had stock on hand for collection at the merchandise window.
After paying, Wendy at the merchandise window had some trouble locating them, she called in Kevin and they both went above and beyond in trying to locate them, thankfully the food court was close by and in short order they came up to deliver them to me.

Have been a member of Costco for many years and the customer service is always fantastic!
Great selection of goods at great prices, often in bulk, that being said they won‚Äôt always be the cheapest but the member discounted items from week to week can certainly help with the savings.

Have previously bought the big playground that they have on display and two years later it looks brand new and definitely worth the cost.

Membership cost $60 for gold star and $55 for business, with a 100% customer satisfaction guarantee where they will return the membership cost if not satisfied.

The food court is amazing with the Hotdogs and soda with free refills costing $1.99.

name: Costco Wholesale Moorabbin
review_text:
New member experience - Day Zero (0) old

I just wanted to share my unforgettable experience as a new member of Costco in Moorabbin (Member since 25/01/22 6PM). My partner and I joined Costco and right after we got our membership cards, we went straight ahead to food court since we haven't had our lunch. We saw that there's no tables to eat and saw some people were eating while standing or beside the condiment table is. Therefore, we thought that was okay. Fast forward, I saw the sign that 'eating is not allowed'. My partner and I stopped eating right away and decided to eat in the car. I put our food on top of the table in condiment while my partner was getting the drinks for us then suddenly there was this old Asian guy employee (white -haired, apologies I didn't get his name) that went straight to me and said it is not allowed to eat here. I said 'I stopped eating and I'm just waiting for my partner for the drinks and we will go'. He continued cleaning the table and went back again at me and said that 'I should go outside' and I answered him back that 'again, I'm just waiting for my partner to come back'. He shouted and said things that something like it is not his rule, it is management rule etc...' and even challenged me to go with him to the management. And I said, 'I stopped eating the moment I saw the sign, you should have be telling that to the other people who are currently eating and not only to me. He answered back saying 'I didn't see them, I only saw you'.

To cut the story short, after my partner came back for the drinks we went straight home, we didn't even bother to buy anything because of that employee of yours. It is not a healthy environment to have someone like that roaming around the store.

@Costco Moorabbin, I know that that employee of yours might be tired or anything because maybe not all people are not following the rule of 'eating is not allowed inside'. But please train them on how to deal with different kind of people and situations. This is very disappointing for my first experience here in Costco. I will try to look for other Costco branch even if it's farther than to shop around knowing that you have an employee like that.

PS. You can check the cctv (if you have) for the action of your employee when he was talking to me. It's around 1810 onwards.

name: Costco Wholesale Moorabbin
review_text:
Today, I had the worst shopping experience in Costco Moorabin with Customer Service Name starting with A (Chinese-looking young man). I will call his name Axx in this review.

I have been a Costco customer for quite a few years. Today, I dropped by Costco Moorabin and tried to exchange the cooler bag (gift pack) because the one I had had its strand stitched inside the fabric. Axx told me that there was nothing he could do because their promotion was changed. I asked him if there was anything under promotion can be exchanged? He tried to offer me a displayed cooler bag, however, the bag he offered was FULL OF DUST, so I declined this offer. Then he asked me to go to Ringwood or Docklands for exchange, apparently, it would be beyond 15 km restriction and the question is, who on earth is going to travel 20 km to get a free bag? Axx told me the current promotion is a water bottle and he told me that I had to bring a CAN OPENER with the cooler bag in order to get the exchange. That was ridiculous because I had to come to this place and to spend the same amount of time again.

I asked Axx if there is a number that I can call in order to resolve this issue, he passed me a membership team card and told me there was no help I could get from the phone. I asked him if I could talk to a manager onsite, then the supervisor came and he said it was OK TO EXCHANGE to a bottle. Axx STOPPED his supervisor and BY SUGGESTING that I must bring the CAN OPENER in order to exchange, which was quite purposeful, mean and personal. The supervisor was quite nice and tried to resolve the issue, he proposed that I just bring the CAN OPENER next time. However, Axx asked me to GIVE MY MEMBERSHIP CARD and he recorded my name and membership card in the system. He tried his best to put resistance in resolving this issue in a nice way. Well he did it, great work.

This was the worst experience of shopping in my life, My family have been spending tens of thousands of dollars in Costco and I didn't feel respect, trust, professionalism from this customer service guy and I even felt being humiliated by him as if I was a clown who was trying to take the advantage of A FREE WATER BOTTLE from Costco.

Tell me, what was I wrong? Shouldn't I ask to an exchange for a faulty bag just because it is a free item?

I went there to buy a ladies purse
( wallet) after my wife confirmed by phone about its availability. The was not available in Docklands store. So I drove all the way from Essendon to Moorabin for purse purchase only. .....

I had a casual visit around the store. I could not find it. I went to the service desk. A white lady named NENA approached me before I could reach service desk. I told her I am after a ladies purse named SAC wirh a price tag of around 33 AUD. She checked it in computer system and told me that there is nothing she can find. Little annoyed I went back to the sales floor as I am shopping costco since last 6 years. I was sure if its said available over the telephone it is definitely available in the store. I found it on my own after spending 20 minutes. I paid little more than 33Aud for it.

I went back to the same lady NENA , showed her the same purse. She replied that I was asking for a wrong product. Its spelling ard Sak and she was searching for sack. She even did not ask me for spelling while searching.

When I went her first time she barely spent a minute on computer screen. She was more interested in staring me from toe to tip as I was looking little rough after a whole night of driving.

name: Costco Wholesale Moorabbin
review_text:
First time shopping at Costco Moorabbin today with my family and although we enjoyed shopping around, once we met by Emily this afternoon in the register (who made it incredibly difficult for us to purchase our goods), this is our first and last shop at Costco Moorabbin.

As another Costco employee was sanitising the conveyor belt at the register (thank you, btw), we asked if we needed to move the groceries onto the belt (as we saw some customers leaving their groceries in the trolley). She politely said ‚Äúno‚Äù and carried on working.A second later, Emily looks at us and bluntly says, ‚Äúyou‚Äôre going to need to put it up on the register.‚Äù We were a little confused but did it anyway. Then she grumpily said ‚Äúhow am I supposed to see the barcodes! Never mind - I‚Äôll do it myself‚Äù and proceeds to exhale loudly (Not the kind of customer service you would expect at a place that requires you to pay to be a ‚Äúmember‚Äù). So I moved aside and asked mum to present her card.

As many people can agree, this year has been tough, so I wanted to cover my mum‚Äôs groceries/shopping (she is a Costco member). As I went to pay, Emily refused my payment to cover my mums grocery bills because I wasn‚Äôt a member. She made it her intention to be difficult as she stood there refusing my payment and further embarrassing my family in front of other customers.

After an incredibly tough year, you would think people would kinder to each other. Emily, you clearly hate standing there ‚Äòserving‚Äô people - maybe it‚Äôs time look for another job or ask to be relocated to the deli section where you don‚Äôt have ‚Äòdeal‚Äô with customers.

Will await to hear from Costco management though I‚Äôm not sure if this will even be read. At the very least, I hope this is shared with Emily - because customers deserve better service when they are expected to be a ‚Äúmember‚Äù to shop there.

name: Costco Wholesale Moorabbin
review_text:
Got my tyres at Costco.  You pay for what you get.  Don't bother if you want tyres on the spot.  They are booked out.  Go to your regular haunts.  Here, if you have time, you'll get the best service available.  If you need it urgently, you're not their target market.   Anyway, so got 4 tyres at the cheapest price on the market with a buy 3 get 1 free, and booked it in 2 weeks later.  Got a call to confirm booking, and got a call to pick up the car.   Tyres inflated with nitrogen, balanced and old tyres thrown away.  The buy 3 get 1 free was a proper promo.  Other places exclude the installation of the free tyre (so you pay another 20-30 for installation).  The only thing these guys do not have is Wheel Alignment.

I note they give free rotation and balance every 10,000kms, but again, you'll need to book.  I doubt I can rock up and get them to do it on the spot.  As for a flat tyre, they give free puncture repair, but probably only useful if you have a full size spare.  Otherwise knowing how busy they are, just pay the $30 bucks to get it fixed else where.

Long story short, I travelled a long distance just to renew my membership
(this Costco was the closest) because I've had technical issues renewing it online where they've charged me twice. When I went to see Chandi at the membership desk, he bluntly said if I don't plan on shopping here frequently, don't bother renewing or coming back... I'm doing you a favour by renewing my membership when other supermarkets don't charge you a fee for entering their doors. They don't even limit their products like eggs. I never said or did anything offensive in any way, yet he's already looking at me as if I can't afford to be a member... how rude.

I tried to ask him if there were any promotions for signing up and he literally just ignored me and walked off chatting to another staff member. This isn't the first time I've had to deal with rude staff members at the membership desk. Costco Moorabbin, please train your staff to treat its members with respect.

Oh and Chandi, if you're going to smoke, please don't do it at the entrance door. You have "no smoking" signs up for a reason, follow your own policies and stop tarnishing the business.

name: Costco Wholesale Moorabbin
review_text:
So, long time buyer who was always happy with the products Costco provides.

First time actually interacting with customer service and it was...an experience.

For those who don't know, Costco checks *everyone's* receipt as they leave and as it happens, this time I had accidentally thrown mine out with some serviettes.

Thus I discovered I could not leave with my single $16.00 item until I had satisfied the staff that I had paid for it.

To quote: ‚Äúyou can get the receipt, or you can leave the item‚Äù

How do I get the receipt? Surely it would be trivial as they scanned my card and my purchase..not even close.

Couldn't say where I checked out as they had closed registers since I wen; so that option wasn‚Äôt there and wasn‚Äôt exactly gonna start lining up randomly.

I tried a cursory search through the bins to no success.

Wend back and basically forced the issue of how I could leave with my purchase.

It was then I discovered the fix: the store manager has to decide if you are a thief or not, either via their own intuition, or video footage.

‚ÄúIt's the policy‚Äù

So why 2 stars?

Technically, nothing is wrong with the product or the staff, they must be commended for following both the letter of the policy as well as its spirit:

‚ÄúShoppers are thieves until proven otherwise‚Äù

So, if you are happy shopping under the assumption of being a crook, this is the place for you.

review_text:
Common, guys,
Of course if you're into slice of pizza toppled with "amazing "ice cream"  then  of course it is worth to shed $60 on the membership.
I find Costco not competitive in many aspects.
1. A lot of products, especially fruits and veggies are actually more expensive than in other supermarkets.
2. Lots of processed food items, if not all of them have canola oil in the recipe composition. It is the cheapest and very bad oil, detrimental to your blood vessels and your health. And they are not cheap either.
3. Some good and sometimes cheaper than in other places products disappear after a short term. Examples are smoked rainbow trout for around $18 a kilo, smoked sardines - in 3 jars package for under $12 and so on.
Some items are actually cheaper, like quinoa or chia seeds but other supermarkets are catching up. On the balance I do not see enough value to renew my membership.

name: Costco Wholesale Moorabbin
review_text:
This was my first visit to Costco Moorabbin with my boyfriend‚Äôs family. We were refused entry when we arrived there because we had 5 members in the group. 4 members lived in the same address while I was the only person who lived elsewhere, which was notified to the staff members.

We weren‚Äôt aware of the policy that stipulated only 2 people were allowed to visit with a member. The policy was enforced by the staff members at the entrance and duty manager in a really unprofessional manner. They insisted  that we took another membership, which we eventually did because we didn‚Äôt have any other option. We travelled a considerable distance to get there and needed to purchase items for an event the next day.

They made us stand outside until we obtained the other membership despite it was raining and cold outside. I also witnessed how the staff members at the entrance were sarcastically laughing pointing at my boyfriend  which gave the impression it was racial discrimination rather than a business trying to enforce a policy.

Once we got in we realised that there no staff members around to help customers. We walked out of the store without a particular product we wanted to purchase because we were unable to find it and not being able to find someone to help us. The bad experience didn‚Äôt end there, once at the restaurant the staff member behind the counter was rude and he was raising his voice at the customers. The drink machines and sauces were empty and no effort was made to refill them.
The service inside would have been much better if the management put the same effort that they put to keep members outside. Strongly discourage anyone from visiting this outlet. Disappointing to see the level of service from a reputed International brand.

review_text:
An example of COSTCO management policies in action:

Hi, could we have a look around to see if we like the store before committing.
Sorry, you will have to purchase a membership first otherwise not allowed in.
That's a nuisance. I had to drive quite far to this out-of-the-way store.
OK can I purchase the membership, have a look and get the membership refunded on the way out.  Yes you can but then you cannot come back again for 12 months.
Whaaaat??? Guess where I am not going to be shopping...

The restaurant food is tasty and cheap. Still waiting for the gate to open at the Boundary Road entrance, hopefully soon. EDIT: The Boundary Rd entrance is open now yay!

name: Costco Wholesale Moorabbin
review_text: Bulk buy in a low price, specially if we talk about the petrol... you cannot beat the price anywhere else. Im sorry to hear some complaints from other costco member regarding their membership card being declined. You cannot go in store without a proper membership card, it should be a physical card that can scan electronically in cashier payment method. You cannot record your card on your mobile device, coz the reason being the card must be swipe electronically otherwise the cashier scanner wont recognize the barcode on your phone screen. If in any circumstances you lost your membership card, just go to the membership desk and we will happily replace it for you anytime. Remember before you sign the membership please read the rules and regulation regarding your membership, stating in the regulations that you should have a membership card with you prior entering Costco warehouse. A membership card that we can check if it is you are the owner of the card or not. Thank you.
